AB  - Berth allocation at container ports is a critical operational bottleneck affecting port throughput and vessel waiting time. This study develops a digital shadow for a major seaport, continuously updated with AIS vessel data and terminal operating system (TOS) logs. A mixed-integer linear programming (MILP) model is solved using Benders decomposition over a rolling time horizon, leveraging real-time port state from the digital shadow. The approach is validated against historical data from Busan New Port (a large port handling approximately 8 million TEU/year), achieving a 15.7% reduction in average vessel waiting time. The digital shadow constitutes the data integration and operational state (L2) layer, while the MILP solver provides decision support (L3). Applicability to brownfield ports with legacy TOS is discussed, with integration challenges identified as a key limitation.
