AB  - Automated guided vehicles (AGVs) play a central role in horizontal transport operations within automated container terminals (ACTs). This paper proposes a cyber-physical system (CPS) for real-time AGV dispatching and routing. The CPS architecture consists of a physical layer (AGV sensors, QR code readers), a communication layer (5G V2X), and a digital twin layer (virtual fleet model with bidirectional synchronization). A deep reinforcement learning (DRL) agent trained in the DT environment is deployed for real-time dispatching decisions. Simulations in AnyLogic with 150 AGVs show that the DRL policy reduces average AGV travel time by 23% compared to first-come-first-served heuristics. The closed-loop feedback between the DT and the physical AGV fleet is partially realized (L4), with full autonomy (L5) as future work. The system is validated at a large automated container terminal with throughput exceeding 3 million TEU/year.
