AB  - Port-Hamiltonian systems provide a powerful mathematical framework for modeling physical systems by emphasizing energy exchange through ports. This paper investigates a class of port-Hamiltonian formulations applicable to mass-spring-damper networks, with applications to mechanical vibration analysis. We derive the Dirac structure underlying the system and prove energy preservation properties. A passivity-based controller is designed ensuring asymptotic stability. Numerical simulations confirm the energy-balancing properties. Applications to electrical circuits and hydraulic systems are discussed. The port-Hamiltonian approach is shown to generalize classical Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics, offering compositional modeling advantages for complex multi-physics systems.
