AB  - Container orchestration platforms such as Kubernetes rely on Linux namespaces and cgroups to isolate Docker containers, but network port exposure remains a significant attack surface. This paper analyzes side-channel attacks targeting container network port mappings in multi-tenant Kubernetes deployments. We demonstrate that an adversary can infer inter-container communication patterns through SMT execution port timing analysis. A novel port isolation policy using eBPF-based network filtering is proposed, reducing information leakage by 94% with less than 2% throughput overhead. Our evaluation covers eight real-world microservices architectures deployed on Kubernetes 1.28. Countermeasures include strict network port binding, container network policy enforcement, and NUMA-aware scheduling to minimize cross-container cache sharing.
