TI  - Digital twin-driven real-time collaborative scheduling for automated container terminals: a closed-loop framework integrating IoT and reinforcement learning
PY  - 2024
T2  - International Journal of Production Research
VL  - 62
IS  - 14
SP  - 5120
EP  - 5143
DO  - 10.1080/00207543.2024.2301001
AB  - Container terminals are increasingly adopting digital twin (DT) technology to improve operational efficiency. This paper proposes a digital twin-driven real-time collaborative scheduling framework for U-shaped automated container terminals (ACTs). The framework integrates an IoT-based data collection layer, an operational state model (L2), and a reinforcement learning (RL) agent (L3) that leverages the DT for decision support. A physical entity model of quay cranes, yard equipment, and AGVs is synchronized with a virtual entity through bidirectional real-time data flow. Experiments on a real container terminal with throughput of 2.3 million TEU/year demonstrate that the proposed approach reduces makespan by 18.3% compared to rule-based heuristics. The closed-loop feedback mechanism (L5) is partially demonstrated in simulation, confirming scalability to large-scale ports.
