TI  - Towards a digital twin for container port berth scheduling: an agent-based simulation approach with real-time data integration
PY  - 2023
T2  - Computers and Operations Research
VL  - 156
SP  - 106237
DO  - 10.1016/j.cor.2023.106237
AB  - Berth scheduling at container ports is a combinatorial optimization problem with significant operational impact. This paper proposes an agent-based simulation model integrated with real-time data to function as a lightweight digital twin for berth scheduling. The simulation model captures vessel arrival patterns, quay crane assignment, and berth occupancy dynamics using data from the terminal's TOS. A rolling-horizon optimization heuristic is embedded in the simulation to generate berth schedules with a 4-hour planning horizon. The framework constitutes a decision support system (L3) with simulation-based what-if capabilities (L4). Validation against 60 days of operational data from a small container terminal (under 500,000 TEU/year) in Vietnam demonstrates scheduling feasibility. The lightweight Python implementation requires minimal computational resources, making it suitable for resource-constrained port environments in Southeast Asia and developing countries.
