TI  - Closed-loop autonomous control for container terminal operations: a digital twin-based multi-agent system with self-adaptive scheduling
PY  - 2025
T2  - IEEE Transactions on Automation Science and Engineering
VL  - 22
IS  - 1
SP  - 445
EP  - 460
DO  - 10.1109/TASE.2025.3401567
AB  - Achieving closed-loop autonomy (L5) in container terminal operations requires seamless integration of real-time data, decision-making, verification, and feedback control. This paper presents a digital twin-based multi-agent system (MAS) for autonomous container terminal management. The DT maintains a comprehensive real-time model of the terminal, including vessel queue, quay crane positions, AGV fleet state, and yard occupancy. A multi-agent reinforcement learning (MARL) system continuously generates scheduling decisions that are first verified in the DT simulation before deployment to physical systems, constituting a closed-loop data-to-decision-to-verify-to-feedback cycle. Experiments at a fully automated container terminal (megaport, approximately 12 million TEU/year) demonstrate that the closed-loop system achieves 97.3% of theoretical maximum throughput with zero human intervention in steady-state operations. The system represents the first industrial deployment of L5 autonomy at a major automated container terminal.
