TI  - A survey of digital twin applications in port and maritime logistics: trends, challenges, and future directions
PY  - 2022
T2  - Maritime Economics and Logistics
VL  - 24
IS  - 3
SP  - 487
EP  - 521
DO  - 10.1057/s41278-022-00213-4
AB  - Digital twin (DT) technology is gaining traction across port and maritime logistics applications. This survey reviews 96 publications from 2016 to 2022, covering DT applications in container terminals, bulk terminals, vessel design, ship routing, and maritime logistics chains. For container terminal operations, we identify 38 relevant papers addressing berth allocation, yard management, crane scheduling, and AGV operations. The survey classifies these by application domain, maturity level, and geographic focus. Key trends include increasing adoption of IoT-based data visibility (L1) and growing interest in reinforcement learning for decision support (L3). Simulation and V&V (L4) are more common in vessel design than terminal operations. Research gaps include lightweight DT architectures, federated DT for port clusters, and DT adoption in developing country ports. The survey concludes with a research agenda emphasizing resource-constrained port contexts.
