TI  - Unlocking the potential of digital twins to achieve sustainability in seaports: a systematic review
PY  - 2025
T2  - WMU Journal of Maritime Affairs
VL  - 24
IS  - 1
SP  - 45
EP  - 89
DO  - 10.1007/s13437-025-00312-x
AB  - Seaports are major contributors to maritime emissions and energy consumption. This systematic review examines 129 publications on digital twin (DT) applications for port sustainability, covering environmental monitoring, energy optimization, carbon emission reduction, and green port certification. For container terminal operations, the review identifies DT applications for sustainable crane scheduling, green AGV routing, and cold ironing integration. A sustainability maturity framework overlaid on the L1-L5 DT maturity model is proposed. Findings reveal that most sustainability-focused DT research is at L1-L2, with limited evidence of decision-support (L3) or closed-loop (L5) sustainability optimization. Geographic analysis shows European ports leading in green DT adoption, with Asian ports rapidly catching up. The review highlights a critical research gap for brownfield port sustainability transitions in developing countries, particularly in Southeast Asia and sub-Saharan Africa. A research agenda with six priority themes is proposed.
